<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910102-0099</DOCNO><DOCID>910102-0099.</DOCID><HL>   International:   Peru's Inflation Sets a Record</HL><DATE>01/02/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C19</SO><CO>   LATAM</CO><IN>INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC AND MONETARY INDICATORS (IEI)</IN><LP>   LIMA, Peru -- Inflation for 1990 registered 7,650%, thehighest in Peru's history, the National Statistics Institutesaid. Prices rose 23.7% in December.   The private consulting firm Cuanto said inflation for 1990was 10,327% and put inflation for December at 26.5%. Cuanto,headed by a former central bank president, is considered anauthoritative analyst of the Peruvian economy. Thepublic-private discrepancy was attributed partly to thetendency of the previous government of President Alan Garciato play down inflation and differences in the methodcalculating the monthly figure.</LP><TEXT>   The 1990 figure marked the third year in a row ofhyperinflation. Inflation reached 2,775% in 1989 and 1,722%in 1988.   December's inflation, the highest monthly figure sinceprices shot up 400% in August, owed largely to economicmeasures announced Dec. 16. These measures raised the priceof gasoline 63% and public utility tariffs between 12% and35%. President Alberto Fujimori imposed harsh austeritymeasures Aug. 8 to try to control rampant inflation and ayawning fiscal deficit. Inflation was running at 3,000%annually when Mr. Fujimori was sworn in July 28.</TEXT></DOC>